<TEI xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0" xmlns:frus="http://history.state.gov/frus/ns/1.0"><text><body><div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1942-08-19T12:00:00-05:00" frus:doc-dateTime-min="1942-08-19T12:00:00-05:00" n="379" subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d379">
                        <note rend="inline" type="source">800.8836/933: Airgram</note>
                        <head>
                            <hi rend="italic">The Ambassador in Cuba</hi> (<persName type="from"><hi rend="italic">Braden</hi></persName>) <hi rend="italic">to the
                                    <gloss type="to">Secretary of State</gloss>
                            </hi>
                        </head>
                        <opener>
                            <dateline rendition="#right">
                                <placeName>
                                    <hi rend="smallcaps">Habana</hi></placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1942-08-19T13:00:00-04:00">August 19,
                                    1942—1 p.m.</date>
                                <lb/> [Received August 21—1:45 p.m.]</dateline>
                        </opener>
                        <p>A–84. Referring to Department’s telegram no. 606 of August 7, 11 p.m. and
                            instruction no. 494 of August 15<note n="45" xml:id="d379fn45">Latter
                                not printed.</note> regarding shipments of Isle of Pines grapefruit
                            it is desired that War Production Board grant exemption from Order M–63
                            immediately for 8,000 crates to leave Habana August 26 on last voyage of
                            one Seatrain vessel. Refrigerator cars for this purpose already are in
                            Habana. Prompt action essential in order that fruit may be in Habana for
                            loading before date mentioned. Cuba Representative War Shipping
                                Administration<note n="46" xml:id="d379fn46">W. S.
                                Loudermilk.</note> concurs in this recommendation.</p>
                        <closer>
                            <signed>
                                <hi rend="smallcaps">Braden</hi>
                            </signed>
                        </closer>
                    </div>
                    </body></text></TEI>